  <!-- How Belt Conveyors Work -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Technical Overview</div>
      <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How Belt Conveyors <span class="text-accent">Work</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>A belt conveyor consists of a continuous belt loop, a drive pulley (head pulley) powered by a motor, an idler pulley (tail pulley) that provides tension, and a support structure that carries the belt and products. The belt wraps around the head and tail pulleys, with the top surface (carry side) transporting products and the bottom surface (return side) traveling back empty.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Belt Support Methods</h3>
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Slider bed</strong> conveyors support the belt on a flat plate or wear strips (typically UHMW). This provides a solid surface for precise positioning and is common in packaging applications. <strong class="text-ink">Roller bed</strong> conveyors support the belt on a series of small rollers, reducing friction for longer conveyors and heavier loads. <strong class="text-ink">Troughed</strong> configurations use angled idler rollers to form a U-shape for bulk material containment.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Drive Systems</h3>
        <p>Most belt conveyors use an AC gearmotor driving the head pulley directly or through a chain/belt transmission. <a href="/resources/automated-conveyor-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Variable frequency drives</a> (VFDs) allow speed adjustment. For precise positioning, servo drives provide accurate stop/start control for <a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">indexing applications</a>. <a href="/resources/conveyor-motors-drives/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Motor sizing</a> depends on belt length, speed, product weight, and incline angle.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Belt Tensioning</h3>
        <p>Proper belt tension is critical for tracking and drive efficiency. Tensioning methods include screw take-up (manual adjustment via threaded rods), gravity take-up (weighted pulley provides constant tension), and automatic take-up (pneumatic or spring-loaded). Insufficient tension causes belt slippage. Excessive tension accelerates bearing and belt wear.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Belt Tracking</h3>
        <p>Belt tracking keeps the belt centered on the pulleys and frame. Crowned pulleys (slightly larger diameter at center) naturally guide the belt to center. Tracking adjustments at the tail pulley correct persistent mistracking. Training idlers (self-aligning rollers) automatically correct belt drift. Proper tracking prevents edge wear, spillage, and belt damage.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
