  <!-- Belt Materials -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="materials-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Belt Materials</div>
      <h2 id="materials-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Conveyor Belt <span class="text-accent">Materials</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">PVC (Polyvinyl Chloride)</h3>
        <p>The most common belt material for general-purpose packaging conveyors. PVC belts are economical, available in many surface finishes (smooth, rough-top, pattern-top), and suitable for temperatures from 14°F to 180°F. Standard PVC is not FDA-approved for direct food contact. Food-grade PVC variants are available but are being replaced by PU in food applications.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">PU (Polyurethane)</h3>
        <p>Preferred for <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food and beverage applications</a> because PU is FDA-compliant, resistant to oils and fats, and easier to clean than PVC. PU belts offer better abrasion resistance and longer service life than PVC but cost more. Temperature range is similar to PVC. White and blue PU is standard for food lines (blue for visibility in case of belt fragments).</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Modular Plastic</h3>
        <p><a href="/conveyor-types/modular-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Modular plastic belts</a> consist of interlocking plastic modules joined by hinge pins. Materials include polypropylene (PP), acetal (POM), and polyethylene (PE), all available in FDA-compliant grades. Modular belts excel in <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sanitary washdown environments</a> because individual modules can be removed for cleaning or replacement. Intralox and Habasit are leading modular belt manufacturers.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Wire Mesh / Metal</h3>
        <p><a href="/conveyor-types/wire-mesh-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Wire mesh belts</a> use woven or welded metal wire for high-temperature applications (baking, cooling, heat treatment) and applications requiring airflow through the belt. Stainless steel mesh handles temperatures to 2000°F+ depending on alloy. Carbon steel is lower cost for non-corrosive, non-food applications. Wire mesh belts are also used for <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/cooling/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cooling conveyors</a> where airflow is needed.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Specialty Materials</h3>
        <p>Specialty belt materials include silicone (high-temperature, non-stick), Teflon/PTFE coating (release properties), anti-static formulations, metal-detectable plastics, and reinforced rubber for heavy-duty bulk handling. Material selection depends on product contact requirements, temperature, chemical exposure, and regulatory compliance (FDA, USDA, 3-A).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="applications-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="applications-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Belt Conveyor <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Primary Packaging</h3>
        <p>Belt conveyors transport products through primary packaging operations: filling, sealing, wrapping, and labeling. Flat belts provide stable, consistent product positioning for accurate filling and labeling. Precision belt conveyors with servo drives support <a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">indexing motions</a> for intermittent packaging machines.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Incline and Decline Transport</h3>
        <p>Belt conveyors handle <a href="/conveyor-types/incline-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">incline and decline transport</a> that roller conveyors cannot. Standard flat belts handle up to 15-20° inclines depending on product friction. <a href="/conveyor-types/cleated-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Cleated belts</a> enable steeper inclines up to 90° (vertical). Rough-top and high-grip belt surfaces extend incline capability without cleats.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Food and Beverage</h3>
        <p><a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Food and beverage plants</a> use belt conveyors for raw ingredient handling, product transport between processing steps, and finished goods packaging. <a href="/conveyor-types/modular-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Modular plastic belts</a> dominate wet environments. <a href="/conveyor-types/wire-mesh-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Wire mesh belts</a> carry products through <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/bakery/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">bakery ovens</a>, fryers, and <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/cooling/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cooling tunnels</a>.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Small Parts and Components</h3>
        <p>Belt conveyors transport small parts, components, and assemblies that would fall between roller conveyor gaps. Flat belt conveyors with side <a href="/components/guide-rails/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">guide rails</a> contain small items. <a href="/conveyor-types/vacuum-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Vacuum belt conveyors</a> grip flat, lightweight items (labels, cartons, pouches) that standard friction cannot hold.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Bags, Pouches, and Flexible Packaging</h3>
        <p>Flexible packaging (bags, pouches, pillow packs) cannot travel on roller conveyors because they conform to roller gaps. Belt conveyors provide the continuous surface these products require. Gentle-handling belts with soft surfaces prevent puncturing or crushing delicate pouches.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Selection Criteria -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="selection-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Guide</div>
      <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Selecting a <span class="text-accent">Belt Conveyor</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Belt conveyor selection involves matching belt type, material, width, and speed to your product and application requirements.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">1. Product characteristics.</strong> Consider product weight (determines belt strength and motor sizing), dimensions (determines belt width), bottom surface (smooth, irregular, soft, rigid), temperature (hot products require heat-resistant belts), and sensitivity (fragile products need soft or cushioned belts).</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">2. Environmental requirements.</strong> <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Food contact</a> requires FDA-compliant materials. Washdown environments require sealed components and corrosion-resistant construction. High or low temperatures require appropriate belt materials. Chemical exposure requires compatible belt and frame materials.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">3. Incline angle.</strong> Calculate the incline angle from floor rise and horizontal run. Select belt type based on maximum incline capability: flat belt (15-20°), rough-top (25-30°), <a href="/conveyor-types/cleated-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cleated</a> (up to 90°). Higher inclines require slower speeds.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">4. Speed and throughput.</strong> Calculate required belt speed from throughput and product spacing. Higher speeds require more robust belt construction, larger motors, and attention to product stability at load/unload points.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">5. Accumulation needs.</strong> Belt conveyors do not accumulate as easily as <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyors</a>. If accumulation is needed, consider a belt conveyor with a <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller accumulation section</a>, or a modular plastic belt with low-friction top surface that allows slip accumulation.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">6. Cleaning and maintenance.</strong> Evaluate cleaning requirements and <a href="/resources/conveyor-parts/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">maintenance access</a>. <a href="/conveyor-types/modular-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Modular plastic belts</a> are easiest to clean and repair (individual modules replace without removing the entire belt). Fabric belts may require more frequent replacement in abrasive or wet environments.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

